# Zysect Security Rules
# These rules apply in every project that ships this file.

## After generating code

After writing or significantly modifying any of the following file types, call the
`scan_file` MCP tool from the `zysect` server:

- Any file that touches authentication (login, register, session, JWT, OAuth)
- Any file that queries a database (Supabase, Prisma, Drizzle, pg, mysql2, SQLite)
- Any file that handles file uploads or multipart form data
- Any API route handler or Next.js server action
- Any file that imports from an external service SDK (Stripe, Twilio, SendGrid, etc.)
- Any file that references environment variables (process.env.*, import.meta.env.*)

## Tool to call

```
zysect.scan_file({
  file_path: "<relative path of the file you just wrote>",
  file_content: "<complete source code of the file>"
})
```

## If findings are returned

- Severity P0: Fix immediately before returning the code to the user.
- Explain the vulnerability in plain language, show the fix inline, then confirm
  the scan passes clean before presenting the final output.
- Never present code with an open P0 finding as complete.

## Scope

Only call `scan_file` on files you generate or substantially edit in this session.
Do not retroactively scan the entire codebase on every request.
